Speedbar is a program for Emacs which can be used to summarize
information about the current buffer.  It's inspiration was the classic
"explorer" often used in modern development environments.

Speedbar displays a tall narrow frame in which a classic tree-view is
shown.  This tree view defaults to containing a list of files.  These
files can be "expanded" to list tags inside, or files in a directory.
Each file or tag can be jumped to immediately.

Speedbar expands upon classic "explorer" windows by constantly
maintaining context with the user.  The "current buffer" file is always
highlighted, and when directories are switched, speedbar follows.
Speedbar also mimics the classic explorer by providing multiple display
modes.  These modes come in two flavors.  Major display modes remain
consistent across buffers, and minor ones appear only when a buffer of
the applicable type is shown.  This provides authors of other packages
to provide speedbar summaries customized to their tastes.

Throughout this manual, activities are defined as "clicking on", or
"expanding" items.  Clicking means using @kbd{mouse-2}.  Expanding has a
more complex meaning  @xref{Basic Navigation}.

