@node Introduction, Basic Navigation, , Top
@comment  node-name,  next,  previous,  up
@chapter Introduction
@cindex introduction

Speedbar can be started using the command @kbd{M-x speedbar RET} or from
the menu bar in versions of Emacs with speedbar installed by default.
The first thing speedbar does is attempt to create a new frame.  On X
windows, or under Windows NT, speedbar's frame is twenty characters
wide, and attempts to mimic the height of the frame from which it was
started.  It then places itself to the left or right of the frame you
started it from.

Speedbar's relationship with the frame you started it from is very
important.  This frame is the "attached frame" which speedbar always
uses as a reference point.  Once started speedbar watches this frame,
and attempts to make it's contents relevant to whatever buffer is
currently loaded into the attached frame.  In addition, all requests
made in speedbar that require the display of some buffer will display in
the attached frame.

If you are using speedbar in terminal mode, the new frame appears the
normal size, as one would expect in a terminal.  Since it is not
visible, speedbar is always in "slowbar" mode, where no tracking is done
unless speedbar is explicitly requested again.

The function to use when switching between frames using the keyboard is
`speedbar-get-focus'.  This function is a toggle between frames, and is
especially useful to bind to a key in terminal mode @xref{Customizing}.

