@node Basic Keybindings, Basic Visuals, Basic Navigation, Basic Navigation
@comment  node-name,  next,  previous,  up
@section Basic Keybindings
@cindex keybindings

These keybindings are common across all modes:
@table @kbd
@item delete, SPC
@cindex scrolling
Scroll up and down one page.
@item Q
@cindex quitting
Quit speedbar, and kill the frame.
@item q
Quit speedbar, and hide the frame.  This makes it faster to restore the
speedbar frame.
@item g
@cindex refresh
Refresh whatever contents are in speedbar.
@item t
@cindex slowbar
Toggle speedbar to and from slowbar mode.  In slowbar mode, frame
tracking is not done.
@item n, p
@cindex navigation
Move to the next or previous item.  A summary of that item will be
displayed in the attached frame's minibuffer.
@item M-n, M-p
Move to the next or previous item in a restricted fashion.  If a list is
open, the cursor will skip over it.  If the cursor is in an open list,
it will not leave it.
@item C-M-n, C-M-n
Move forwards and backwards across extended groups.  This lets you
quickly skip over all files, or directories, or other common sub-item at
the same current depth.
@item C-x b
Switch buffers in the attached frame.
@end table

Speedbar can handle multiple modes, and two are provided by default.
These modes are the File mode, and Buffers mode.  Speedbar provides
accelerators to switch into these different modes.

@cindex mode switching hotkeys
@table @kbd
@item b
Switch into Quick Buffers mode @xref{Buffer Mode}.  After one use, the
previous display mode is restored.
@item f
Switch into Files mode.
@item r
Switch back to whatever the previous mode was.
@end table

Some modes provides groups, lists and tags.  @xref{Basic Visuals}.  When
these are available, some additional common bindings are available.

@cindex common keys
@table @kbd
@item RET, e
Edit/Open the current group or tag.  This behavior is dependent on the
mode.  In general, files or buffers are opened in the attached frame,
and directories or group nodes are expanded locally.
@item +,=
Expand the current group, displaying sub items.
@item -
Contract the current group, hiding sub items.
@end table

@node Basic Visuals, Mouse Bindings, Basic Keybindings, Basic Navigation
@comment  node-name,  next,  previous,  up
@section Basic Visuals
@cindex visuals

Speedbar uses visual queues for indicating different types of data.
These queues are used consistently across the different speedbar modes.

The most basic visual affect is color, and mouse highlighting.  Anything
the mouse highlights can be clicked on. @xref{Mouse Bindings}.  Anything
not colored will also not be clickable.

Text in speedbar consists of three different types of data.  Plaintext,
such as labels or separators, Groups, and tags.  Some items also get
boolean flags.

@subsubsection Plaintext

Plaintext generally starts in column 0, without any special symbols.  In
File mode, the current directory label is like this.  In buffers mode,
different buffer groups are prefixed with a description of what they are
like.

Plaintext will appear white, and not be clickable.

@subsubsection Groups
@cindex groups

Groups can appear at different levels, and are prefixed with a + in some
sort of "box".  In files mode, directories are "groups" where the + is
surrounded by angle brackets like this:

@example
<+> include
<-> src
 [+] foo.c
@end example

In this example, we see both open and closed directories, in addition to
a file.

In all modes, a group can be "edited" by pressing @kbd{RET}, meaning a
file will be opened, or a directory explicitly opened in speedbar.  A
group can be expanded or contracted using @kbd{+} or
@kbd{-}. @xref{Basic Keybindings}.

Sometimes groups may have a ? in it's indicator "box".  This means that
it is a group type, but there are no contents, or no known way of
extracting contents of that group.

@subsubsection Tags
@cindex tags

Tags are the leaf nodes of the system.  Tags are generally prefixed with
a simple plaintext symbol character, such as ">".  Tags can only be
jumped to using @kbd{RET} or @kbd{e}.

@subsubsection Boolean Flags

Sometimes a group or tag is given a boolean flag.  These flags appear as
extra plaintext characters at the end of the line.  At the moment, only
Files mode uses boolean flags, such as a @asis{*} to indicate that a
file has been checked out of a versioning system.

@c Note to self, update these to sub-nodes which are more relevant.
@xref{File Mode}, @xref{Version Control}.

@subsubsection Color Queues

Each type of Group, item indicator, and label is given a different
color.  The colors chosen are dependent on a light or dark background.
Of important note is that the "current item", which may be a buffer or
file name, is highlighted red, and underlined.  In addition, the cursor
is generally moved to that line.

Colors can be customized from the group @code{speedbar-faces}.  Some
modes, such as for Info, will use the Info colors instead of default
speedbar colors as an indication of what is currently being displayed.

@node Mouse Bindings, Displays Submenu, Basic Visuals, Basic Navigation
@comment  node-name,  next,  previous,  up
@section Mouse Bindings
@cindex mouse bindings

Speedbar's display is made of of different textual queues which provide
buttons which can be clicked on @xref{Basic Visuals}.  Anything that
highlights can be clicked on with the mouse, or affected by the menu.

In general, these are the bindings:
@table @kbd
@item mouse-1
Move cursor to that location
@item mouse-2, double-mouse-1
Activate the current button.   @kbd{double-mouse-1} is a basic double
click, and useful for windows users with only two button mice.
@item SHIFT-mouse-2, SHIFT-double-mouse-1
@cindex power click
Power click, which is the same as activate, except some other useful
thing happens.  If a group @code{+} is clicked, any caches are flushed,
and subitems re-read.  If it is a buffer or file, it will be opened in a
new frame.
@item mouse-3
Activate speedbar menu.  The item selected affects the line clicked, not
the line where the cursor was. 
@item mode-line mouse-1
Activate the menu.  This affects the item the cursor is on, since the
mouse was not clicked on anything.
@item C-mouse-1
Buffers sub-menu.  The buffer in the attached frame is switched.
@end table

Also, when speedbar is selected, and the mouse moves over items, details
of that item should be displayed in the minibuffer of the attached
frame.  Sometimes this can contain extra information such as file
permissions, or tag location.

@node Displays Submenu, , Mouse Bindings, Basic Navigation
